05423nam a22008055i 9780674293397DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742933977 a10.4159/97806742933972doi  a(DE-B1597)642338  a(OCoLC)1381475884  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aBUS0680002bisacsh1 aLiu, Zongyuan Zoe, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSovereign Funds :bHow the Communist Party of China Finances Its Global Ambitions /cZongyuan Zoe Liu. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. China’s Evolving Perspectives on Foreign Exchange Reserves -- t2. Central Huijin -- t3. China Investment Corporation -- t4. State Administration of Foreign Exchange -- t5. Sovereign Funds in a Changing Global Geoeconomic Landscape -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe first in-depth account of the sudden growth of China’s sovereign wealth funds and their transformative impact on global markets, domestic and multinational businesses, and international politics.One of the keys to China’s global rise has been its strategy of deploying sovereign wealth on behalf of state power. Since President Xi Jinping took office in 2013, China has doubled down on financial statecraft, making shrewd investments with the sovereign funds it has built up by leveraging its foreign exchange reserves. Sovereign Funds tells the story of how the Communist Party of China (CPC) became a global financier of surpassing ambition.Zongyuan Zoe Liu offers a comprehensive and up-to-date analysis of the evolution of China’s sovereign funds, including the China Investment Corporation, the State Administration of Foreign Exchange, and Central Huijin Investment. Liu shows how these institutions have become mechanisms not only for transforming low-reward foreign exchange reserves into investment capital but also for power projection. Sovereign funds are essential drivers of the national interest, shaping global markets, advancing the historic Belt and Road Initiative, and funneling state assets into strategic industries such as semiconductors, fintech, and artificial intelligence. In the era of President Xi, state-owned financial institutions have become gatekeepers of the Chinese economy. Political and personal relationships with prestigious sovereign funds have enabled Blackstone to flourish in China and have fueled the ascendance of private tech giants such as Alibaba, Ant Finance, and Didi.As Liu makes clear, sovereign funds are not just for oil exporters. The CPC is a leader in both foreign exchange reserves investment and economic statecraft, using state capital to encourage domestic economic activity and create spheres of influence worldwide.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Development / Economic Development.2bisacsh  abonds.  acommodity.  acovid 19.  aelites.  aequity.  agoing out policy.  ahong kong.  aopening up.  apboc.  apeoples bank.  arenminbi.  arussia.  asecurity.  asilk road fund.  astate council.  astocks.  aunited states.  azhou xiaochuan.  azhu rongji.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Business and Economics 2023 Englishz978311131907008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics 2023z9783111318134oZDB-23-DBV08iTit